🔁 Full Mapping Pipeline (Who does what?)
File Offset (bytes)
   ↓
Logical Block (filesystem block)
   ↓
Physical Block (disk block number)
   ↓
Sector (hardware unit)
🧠 Layer-by-Layer Responsibility
✅ 1. Offset → Logical Block
👉 Done by: Filesystem layer (with help from VFS)

Flow:
You call:

read(fd, buf, size)
Kernel knows:

file->f_pos  (offset)
Conversion:
logical_block = offset / block_size
Who does it?
Generic helpers: filemap_read()

Filesystem-aware logic: Filesystem layer (ext4/xfs)

👉 VFS passes the request, but
👉 Filesystem understands block size → does actual calculation

✅ 2. Logical Block → Physical Block
👉 Done by: Filesystem (MOST IMPORTANT STEP)

This is where filesystem intelligence lives.

Example (ext4):
Uses:

Inode

Extent tree

Function:
ext4_map_blocks()
Conversion:
logical_block → physical_block
👉 This mapping depends on:

File fragmentation

Allocation strategy

Extents

✔️ This is 100% filesystem responsibility

✅ 3. Physical Block → Sector
👉 Done by: Block Layer (and partially FS provides input)

Conversion:
sector = physical_block × (block_size / 512)
Who does it?
Filesystem provides:

physical_block + block_size
Block layer converts into:

bio

sector-based I/O

👉 Final responsibility: Block Layer

✅ 4. Sector → Device Operation
👉 Done by: Device Driver

Converts:

sector → hardware command
Example:

SATA command

NVMe submission queue entry

🎯 FINAL ANSWER (Short & Precise)
Conversion	Layer Responsible
Offset → Logical Block	Filesystem (via VFS context)
Logical → Physical Block	Filesystem (ext4/xfs)
Physical Block → Sector	Block Layer
Sector → Hardware I/O	Device Driver
🔥 Super Important Insight
👉 Many people get this wrong:

❌ VFS does NOT map blocks

❌ Block layer does NOT understand files

✔️ Correct:

Filesystem = mapping expert

Block layer = I/O executor

